Overview

Goal:

Identify current Life(NONMG) policy holders who are likely to buy a Moneyguard(MG) policy.

Data Sources:

KBM data, policy level data, Rx data(Excluded from Final Model) Filtered to Life and MG Products only
Re-coded to MG and NONMG 485,372 policies

Data Timeframe:

1/1/2000-12/31/2015

Modeling Response:

Either MG or NONMG
NONMG > MG

Classification or Regression Model:

Classification

Deliverables:

Policy number list of NONMG policies with high probability of purchasing MG.

Data Aggregation & Cleaning

Data Sources

Policy data was queried from ISL history table for all policies from 1/1/2000 to 12/31/2015. Data was culled based on product type; excluding all policy types except Moneyguard, IUL, VUL, TM, and GUL.

KBM data was queried for the cleaned policy list from ISL history,the kbm data is found in the INSIGHT_RPT database, the result included about 300 variables. These data were last updated in March 2016. These data include demographic, consumer behavior, and survey response datatypes. A detailed description of all the data in this model is provided in appendix A.

Rx data was queried for the cleaned policy list through Lifewriter(Winrisk). The RX data is counts of RX fills per person at the time of their initial underwriting for a life policy. Three categories exists; 1 is the least severe, 3 is the most severe. The date of the data depends on the effective date of the policy.

Policy State, and zip code were queried from the Name_table in Winrisk as well.

APS and Labs data presence and absence was initially included but later found to be problematic for the classification; as well as Underwriting ratings.

Data Cleaning

All the data collated together resulted in 330 variables to predict the policy class of either Moneyguard or Non-Moneyguard.Duplicate records were identified and deleted.

All variables that were considered id columns (100% unique) were excluded from the data to avoid prediction bias. Many of the variables contained NA or missing values; in this case we implemented a 50% rule and imputed the values. Those variables with more than 50% of the data missing were deleted. For the remaining Nas in numeric data they were filled using the column median.For the factor and logical variables the Nas were imputed based on the most common value in that variable. Variables with near zero variance were also removed from the data set to improve modeling efficiency.

Exploratory Data Analysis

Dual policy holders

As part of the exploratory analysis policy holders that currently held both Life and MG policies were identified using the filtered data set and the DEDUPE_ID variable, which indicated more than one policy for that individual. Based on the dedupe id and the policy effective date we were able to identify individual who first purchased a Life policy and at a later date purchased a MG policy. There were 1100 of these dual policy holders who made the transition that we were interested in modeling in this effort. This groups attributes in terms of variable values provided a snapshot of what our target population may be. Although, the size of this group was markedly small compared to our 400,000 total data set. This subset transition class of observations was used as a comparative base line for further variable selection.

Variable Selection

Considering the numerous variables in the initial data set a traditional univariate or bivariate variable review would be inefficient. An initial model build was created to statistically identify the important predictors within our variables. This initial model was created using a random forest classification built and calibrated to provide a list of variable importance in modeling MG and NONMG policies. In addition, a random forest model was built using the transition class observations (those 1100 dual policyholders). The top 30 variables from both the MG and NONMG random forest model as well as the transition class model were compared. The Rx class count data was originally included in this top 30; however, after further review the Rx data was removed and the final model was refit excluding Rx data.

Univariate review of selected

A univariate review of these selected top 30 variables was completed. Each distribution was broken down by the MG and NonMG classes. The figure below is an example of those distribution plots.

Variable Recoding

An initial step-wise logistic regression model illuminated the issue of high dimensional within the kbm categorical variables. Although, these variables were still strongly informing the model their high dimensions were limiting the overall number of variables that could be included as well as the assessment of the overall impact of the individual variables themselves.For example, age range variable included a category for each 5 year increment and it was determined through discussion that we could reduce all the five year increments under age 46 to one single category.The following variables were re-coded:

  • Age Range
  • Generation spending clusters
  • Net worth
  • Investable Assets
  • Household composition
  • Prepaid Funeral Offer
  • Income
  • Auto Insurance Offer

Composite variables

After remodeling with the re-coded variables there was still a need for additional model performance improvement. Distinct groupings within the distributions of the re-coded variables were identifies within the MG and NONMG classes. Based on these clear strong informers composite variables were created by re-coding the included variables to zero and one delineating the positive impact on classifying MG policies as one. Then the variables that logically combined well were summed to provide a composite variable with a range of impact values for MG policies. The following illustration explains the process.

List of Composite Variables:

  • Married + 50 yo + female
  • Married + 50 yo +debt class
  • Married + 50 yo + debt class+ investable assets
  • Married + 50 yo + income
  • Married + 50 yo + investable assets
  • Rx Rating 1 +Tobacco Rating
  • Rx Rating 2 + Tobacco Rating
  • Rx Rating 3 + Tobacco Rating
  • State + Rating
  • Zip + Rating

Variable List Re-expanded

With expanded model convergence space created by the re-coding of variables, additional previously excluded variables were added back in to the modeling process. Instead of only including the top 15 variables we compared the top 30 variables in the original MG and NONMG model with the top 30 variables in the transition class model. A total of 19 variables were found in both models, so those overlap variables were included. Additionally, the ratings classes, Rx data, the composite variables and ZIP code, state, Census Statistical Area were included in the next modeling phase.

Principle Component Analysis

In continued pursuit of data dimension reduction a PCA was calculated based on the above data.A PCA is an orthogonal data transformation with components equal to the number of data dimensions.Each component was a relatively small portion of the variance.

Model Testing

Types of models: Logistic Regression, Random Forest, Tree Models

The first model comparison build was a Logistic regression model compared to a random forest model. The step wise logistic regression routine landed on the following model formation:

This fit excluded the following variables: * Name_SEX * ESTDebt30 * ESTInc30 * ESTInv30 * m50dincinv Model Review of performance indicated the model was over fit,see the ROC curve below presented with a reference ROC in blue.

The Random Forest model based on the same set of variables appeared to perform well. Performance indicators below:

Model Development

After model performance demonstrated the over fitting with PCA, those components were excluded from the next iteration of model building. The random forest model performed well even with the exclusion of the PCA variables. This model provided classification results, e.g.the predicted output was a class of either MG or NONMG.

In order to support scoring of policies for ranking in terms of confidence in those predictions a tree model was implemented which returned a probability score of being a MG. This tree model is functionally similar to random forest yet much more efficient and not quite as robust. This allowed for a ranking of confidence in the random forest model predictions. The tree model has to be tuned with a complexity error evaluation and then re-run to reach an appropriate model for predictions.The tree model was built with the same input variables.

In an additional step of performance evaluation we created a class prediction based on the tree predictions greater than 0.5. Evaluating the overlap in class predictions between the random forest and tree model indicted about 60% overlap. This is slightly lower than preferred; however, it is in line with level of variation and disproportionate number of MG to NONMG observations.

A set of random forest model predictions as well as tree model predictions were generated as the policies to implement in the cross sell program. After discussions with compliance it was determined to remove the RX data from the final model. The impact of removing the RX data from the final model results in an overall accuracy reduction of 2% for the random forest model.

Final Model

The final model is an iteration of random forest and a tree model with the seed set at 1234. The random forest model is a classification with a min split size of 1 and 50 trees; tuning of these parameters was completed through an iterative search of parameter optimization. The 10% data hold out confusion matrix is above:

The final variable importance and variable usage is here:

This model resulted in 60,999 NONMG policies classed as MG.This is a large number and indicates the need for a scoring approach provided by the more simplified tree model.The complexity parameter is optimized in the first iteration of the tree model and then cp is set to that optimum level for the number of trees to grow in the next iteration. A visualization of the impact of cp on relative error is provided here:

The tree model performed well also. In addition the overlap of the tree and random forest model predictions was evaluated.

Appendix A: Long Data Description

Currently we have 3 data sources and 4 data types.

1. KBM data

Survey data obtained from Customer Insights of about 300 variables. These data were used in the App Triage model as well. Generally model predicted indicators of lifestyle behaviors such e.g.spending habits, household structure, and economic indicators.

A subset of 15 out of the 300 variables has been identified to be included in the final model.

GENERS

A segmentation system comprised of five generational groups and 52 unique clusters based on common purchasing power and behavior, lifestyle choices, demographic attributes, socioeconomic status and attitudes.
